Ankara&#39;s gain from the peace settlement is obvious.
First, Erdogan needs all the friends he can get after last month&#39;s failed coup attempt to oust him.
The countless terrorist attacks have also shaken his position.
So are economic motives.
Russian sanctions have caused serious damage, especially the ban on charter flights, which usually ensures the influx of several million Russian tourists to Turkish resorts every year.
The number of tourists decreased by almost 90%.
Russian tour operators and charter companies will also breathe a sigh of relief when regular flights are restored.
They look forward to holiday fever in the Mediterranean at the end of the season.
Already this week, the state TV predicts a decrease in the prices of fruits and vegetables, as the import of Turkish fruits and vegetables will be restored.
As the local newspaper Vedemosti quotes: &quot;Tourists for them, tomatoes for us.&quot;
However, the visit also had other political motives from Moscow&#39;s side.
Ankara is angry with the West for what it sees as a weak response to the coup attempt.
In addition to everything, one can also see the dissatisfaction with the protracted negotiations on joining the EU and the intervention of Putin, who likes to take advantage of the situation that Turkey is alienated from the West.
The Russian leader undoubtedly scored bonus points in Ankara&#39;s eyes by voicing support for its elected government after the coup attempt.
Note that Moscow understands this well, as it itself has a deep-rooted fear of regime change in the country.
The summit, held at this luxurious seaside palace, gave Russia and Turkey a chance to present what one analyst called an &quot;alliance of the outcasts,&quot; two countries that feel ostracized by the West joining forces.
But despite the publicly displayed unity, there are still significant differences of opinion between the two countries.
The main disagreement concerns Syria, where Russia presents itself as a peacemaker, but in fact Russia and Turkey support opposite sides.
After more than three hours of preliminary talks, the two presidents said at a news conference that they had not discussed the matter, speaking on condition of anonymity.
The Turkish president purposefully avoided questions about the differences between the two countries, while President Putin wanted to emphasize them.
There is no clear consensus on how the two countries could find common ground on the Syrian issue.
But after months of openly hostile relations and a potential disaster when NATO member Turkey shot down a Russian warplane, the situation has improved as the two leaders have at least resumed talks.
