The drug can reduce the risk of heart attack by 2 pounds a day.
Thousands of heart attack patients could be treated with a £2-a-day drug as officials recommend it be given to more people and for a longer period of time.
The anticoagulant drug Ticagrelor reduces the risk of recurrent heart attacks in people with heart disease.
These drugs are already prescribed for use 12 months after a heart attack, reducing the risk of a repeat heart attack.
NICE, representing the NHS, recommends taking this medicine for 4 years after a heart attack to further reduce the risk of heart attack in people with cardiovascular problems.
However, NICE, which is currently in charge of the NHS, recommends using this preparation for 4 years after a heart attack to further reduce cardiovascular risk.
Around 140,000 people in England have a heart attack every year and a quarter of those have a repeat heart attack or stroke.
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by the accumulation of fatty substances in the walls of the heart, forming blockages.
If the blockage breaks, it can form a clot, blocking blood flow to the heart and causing a heart attack.
On the other hand, if the thrombus detaches from the blood vessel wall, it can travel further into the bloodstream and block blood access to the brain, causing a heart attack.
People who have had a heart attack are at a higher risk of having another heart attack.
Ticagrelor, manufactured by the British company AstraZeneca and marketed under the name Brilique, reduces the risk of blood clots.
New NICE guidelines published today recommend that people take 90mg of Ticagrelor for 12 months and 60mg twice a day for a further 3 years with aspirin.
Professor Carol Longson, director of health technology at NICE, explains: &quot;Despite the availability of medicines to prevent a repeat heart attack, more than a quarter of people who have had a heart attack go on to have another heart attack or stroke, often with severe consequences.&quot;
Fear of a repeat heart attack can have a negative impact on a person&#39;s quality of life.
Evidence shows that Ticagrelor, when combined with aspirin, is effective in reducing the risk of recurrent heart attacks and heart attacks in people who have already had one.
By tentatively recommending treatment with Ticagrelor, we are pleased to be able to extend treatment options to the thousands of people who will benefit from it.
Given the limited information on the efficacy and safety of Ticagrelor, especially the risk of bleeding, when this medication is used for more than three years, the draft guideline does not recommend its use beyond this period.
