The president who remained in the shadow: Gustav Zemgal - 145.
Friday, August 12, marks 145 years since the birth of the second president of Latvia, Gustavs Zemgals.
Zemgals proclaimed the state of Latvia, but has undeservedly remained in the shadow of the widely described first president of Latvia, Jānis Čakste, and the last president of the pre-war period, Kārlis Ulmanis.
None of our statesmen has defended democracy and the rule of law as much as Zemgals, writes Arnolds Auziņš in the book dedicated to Gustav Zemgals published ten years ago.
In a conversation with the &quot;Delfi&quot; portal, Auziņš emphasizes that Zemgals is one of the rare politicians in high positions who had a sense of humor.
The others are so stiff, always very correct.
He taught not to be like that, nowadays it could be similar to what Raimonds Vējonis is.
&quot;He was someone who is close to the people&quot;, says Auziņš.
Today&#39;s politicians do not know history well, they referred to Karl Ullman as a good leader, but hardly anyone knows how bad he was.
At government meetings, the only person he did not shout at was General Balodis.
Even though he is kind and smiling in pictures, he was hysterical by nature.
&quot;Zemgals with his sense of humor and democracy leaves exactly the opposite impression&quot;, says Auziņš.
In a conversation with &quot;Delfi&quot;, Professor Aivars Stranga of the Faculty of History and Philosophy of the University of Latvia agrees with Auzin&#39;s assessment of Zemgala as a calm and balanced statesman.
He also notes that Zemgals was distinguished by his respect for minorities, regularly inviting Jewish representatives to the presidential palace.
&quot;At that time, this was not a common behavior, after Zemgal&#39;s presidency, Alberts Kviesis took over this tradition&quot;, says the historian.
He was such a quiet and composed person who had to be persuaded to become the president for a long time.
He himself did not pursue it, he simply did not crave fame.
He was also quite critical of himself because he did not know French, but he believed that the president must know it.
&quot;During the presidency, the basics of the French language were learned&quot;, explains Stranga.
Zemgals did not allow himself to be persuaded to run again, he did not really like high positions at all.
In all respects, he is a very respectable person in the history of Latvia, he was already in a serious position before arriving at the presidential palace - he was a highly sought-after notary.
Also, Zemgals managed the famous Zemgals treasury on Suvorova street 3, where the association of storekeepers and moneylenders was located, practically the state of Latvia was created there during government negotiations.
He was always progressive.
Was not a big admirer of Ulmanis, but did not oppose him publicly either.
&quot;In private conversations, he has sometimes expressed that he really doesn&#39;t like Ulmanis&#39; actions,&quot; says Stranga.
Lived a peaceful life, no suspicion of illegality or corruption.
How is Zemgalu remembered today?
It&#39;s a pity, but for a large part, he is only associated with a street in Riga.
He was an absolute democrat, his views were centrist.
&quot;There were no major upheavals during his time, that is, he could be associated with such a really stable presidency,&quot; Stranga sums up.
During the presidency of Gustavus Zemgal, from 1927 to 1930, Latvia&#39;s state visit to Sweden also took place, which indirectly meant full recognition of Latvia in the neighboring country and inclusion in the family of democratic nations of Northern Europe.
On May 28, 1929, Zemgals came to Stockholm on a state visit.
The Swedish King Gustav V&#39;s return visit to Latvia took place on June 29, 1929.
The second president of Latvia was born in 1871, but passed away in January 1939.
Simple ways to help your child deal with tantrums.
I often have to face the fact that parents consider the child&#39;s anger and rage to be something wrong and abnormal.
When a child openly shows his anger - we don&#39;t know how to react, says psychologist Ekaterina Kesa in &quot;Econet&quot;.
The specialist encourages a small conversation about these so natural and human feelings - anger and rage, which everyone periodically experiences.
Aggression is already a physical action directed against another person, and it usually appears when we feel angry.
When we adults are angry, upset, we usually know what is happening to us and how to deal with it.
We can: express, suppress, hide, keep to ourselves, tell our friends or other loved ones about it, we can kick the couch in anger, smoke a cigarette (this is not the best way to dissipate anger!), take a shower, hit a kulak around the table and do other things that we don&#39;t usually do.
We do not direct our aggression towards others because we know various other ways to deal with these emotions.
Children, when anger hits them, do not understand what is happening to them, how to name it and how to live with it.
They can say: &quot;Go away!&quot;, &quot;You&#39;re a fool&quot;, &quot;Bad mom&quot;, &quot;I can&#39;t see you&quot;, &quot;I won&#39;t be friends with you&quot; - and very rarely they can say: &quot;I&#39;m angry with you&quot;.
Children live in a literal sense, they are completely present right here in this moment, they are spontaneous and genuine in showing their feelings, and they are often in the grip of different emotions.
It is very important that parents do not forbid the child to show feelings, including anger, do not be ashamed of it and do not scold, but on the contrary - help the child.
