With his enthusiastic and enthusiastic personality, Rosenthal was the first to arouse interest in the performing arts in the Latvian people.
&quot;In this sense, he was the first love of the Latvian people, which as such will remain forever unforgettable&quot;, that&#39;s what Romans Suta once wrote about the old master of Latvian painting, Janis Rozentāls.
Also in 2016, when the old master&#39;s extensive retrospective exhibition was opened in the restored main building of the Latvian National Art Museum, it is clear - Rozentāls is the first love of Latvian art.
The exhibition was opened on August 12, but it has been available to visitors since August 13 and will be open for viewing until October 30.
The Latvian National Art Museum is honoring the painter Jani Rozentāls (1866-1916) with an extensive retrospective in the newly opened Great Exhibition Hall, whose one hundred and fiftieth birthday is internationally included in the UNESCO calendar of celebrated days.
The retrospective exhibition, which presents more than 150 works, is one of the central events of Janis Rosenthal&#39;s anniversary program.
The selection of works of art is mostly made from the collection of the Latvian National Art Museum, which convincingly represents the main stages and genres of the classicist&#39;s creative activity, stylistic changes and variety of techniques.
In addition, exhibits from the Akseli Gallen-Kallela Museum, the Museum of Writing and Music, the Liepaja Museum, the Tukuma Museum and several private collections in Latvia and Finland were used.
The atmosphere of the turn of the century is revived by the presence of photos, the mobile application of the exhibition reveals the connections of individual works of art with photos taken by the painter himself with his camera for creative purposes.
On the other hand, the Finnish-Latvian partnership &quot;Rozentāls-seura&quot;, named after a Latvian classicist, is simultaneously offering the first stop of a small informative traveling exhibition &quot;With a look in Finland, with a heart in Latvia&quot; at the Latvian National Art Museum.
A similar exhibition with content in English, Finnish and Swedish will be opened in the autumn in the &quot;Virka&quot; gallery in Helsinki.
