The Islamic State has captured 2,000 civilians in Syria.
Islamic State militants have taken about 2,000 civilians captive as human shields while fleeing Manbij in Syria&#39;s Aleppo province, the US-backed Kurdish-Arab alliance and monitors said on Friday.
&quot;We did not shoot at them because they took civilians with them when they fled to Jarabulus,&quot; declared the press representative of the Kurdish Manbij Military Council.
After two months of fighting, the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (QSD), a US-backed Kurdish-Arab alliance in northern Syria, announced on Friday that Manbij had been liberated from jihadists.
The Islamic State captured Manbij in 2014.
The QSD already last week drove most of the &quot;Islamic State&quot; fighters from Manbij, but some remained and showed fierce resistance.
On Friday, however, they left the city, taking prisoners with them.
The Islamists are going to Jarabulus, which is on the Turkish border.
The Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (SOHR), a Syrian activist organization based in London, also reported that the &quot;Islamic State&quot; had kidnapped about 2,000 people.
SOHR reported that the Islamists hijacked the cars of the city&#39;s residents, forced people into them, and then drove them to Jarabulus.
Islamic State fighters have also carried out mass kidnappings in the past.
In January, Islamists abducted more than 400 civilians, including women and children, as they seized territory in Deir ez-Zor province in eastern Syria.
Later, the Islamists released about 270 of the captives.
It is not known how many fighters of the Islamic State escaped from Manbij.
The press representative of the Kurdish Manbij Military Council reported that the QSD managed to rescue 2,500 people held captive by the Islamists in Manbij.
The information collected by SOHR shows that at least 437 civilians, including 105 children, lost their lives in the battle for Manbij.
299 QSD fighters and 1,019 jihadists were killed.
