German researchers debate the number of &quot;victims of the Berlin Wall&quot;.
The death toll along the border of communist-ruled former East Germany could be much higher than previously thought, according to a new study, but doubts remain about the true toll.
According to data released Wednesday by the Berlin Wall Museum Checkpoint Charlie, between 1945 and 1989, 1,841 people who tried to escape from the territory controlled by them were murdered by the communist authorities of Western Germany and later West Germany.
The museum has been studying border-related deaths for years and periodically corrects the death toll.
This year, 11 more deaths have been added to the list, including a six-year-old boy who drowned as his family tried to reach West Germany through what was then Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
Among the new victims of the Berlin Wall are deserters from the Soviet army.
&quot;The final extent of the damage caused by the double evil of communism and socialism has not yet been fully documented,&quot; admits museum director Aleksandra Hildebrandt.
&quot;Our task is to ensure that the graves of those who died trying to escape from the communist-controlled country are maintained and do not disappear,&quot; Hildebrandt&#39;s statement emphasized.
However, other researchers have already questioned the new figures.
&quot;The number 1841 is unconvincing,&quot; says Jochen Staats, an expert on the history of East Germany at the Free University of Berlin, in an interview with the Süddeutsche Zeitung newspaper.
He and other researchers at the Free University of Berlin are currently reviewing possible suspicious deaths at the border, and so far they have been able to confirm only 260 cases.
Previously, researchers estimated that 138 people were murdered by communists at the Berlin Wall alone.
Taking into account the people who died trying to escape through the Baltic Sea or reach the West through the territory of neighboring countries, according to the State, the number of victims could reach about a thousand.
But it is still significantly less than 1841.
One of the reasons for the different number of victims could be the different methodologies.
The Checkpoint Charlie Museum also records all suicides of East German border guards, whether or not they were directly related to their service.
The museum also records deaths that do not involve direct violence.
&quot;If seniors in their 70s and 80s died of heart attacks after contracting border controls,&quot; it must be the result of this &quot;killer border,&quot; Hildebrandt said.
But the State is adamant that a distinction must be made between elderly people who may have died as a result of the mistreatment they experienced and those whose deaths were caused by a long wait in hot weather on a bus at the border.
Regardless, tallying the victims is not easy because communist East German authorities did not collect such statistics, and researchers must sift through documents in various scattered archives, the state says.
However, the State group has recently come across new documents, and therefore it may come up with a new estimate of the number of victims in the near future.
LPF president Pone went to Rio with a coach&#39;s accreditation; itself is a surprise.
Kaspars Pone, the president of the Latvian Swimming Federation (LPF), who has gained notoriety in recent days, has come to the Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro with a coach&#39;s accreditation, but he himself is surprised by it.
On Wednesday, a wide stir was caused by the statements of Olympic swimmer Alona Rybakova&#39;s coach, German Jakubovski, who revealed that Pone decided to go to Rio de Janeiro at the last moment, while the coach had to stay at home.
Initially, swimmers Alona Ribakova and Uvis Kalniņš, coaches Jakubovskis and Dave Collins, as well as the president of the federation Pone were confirmed in the list of riders.
The Latvian Swimming Federation announced five participants for the Olympic Games, and even before the departure, Aldons Vrubļevskis claimed that German will be there and tickets are being sought for him.
&quot;However, obviously for objective reasons he didn&#39;t make it,&quot; said Pone, expressing the opinion that this did not affect Rybakova&#39;s result.
At the federation&#39;s request, Uvja&#39;s coach took it upon himself to help her.
Pone, who is himself a member of the IOC executive committee, sharply criticized the IOC&#39;s actions, shifting the blame to the organization that oversees Olympic sports.
In my view, it is unethical to approve five persons in the LOK executive committee and not remove one of them.
&quot;I don&#39;t know why there was not enough space for the Swimming Federation&quot;, Pone said that the society did not appreciate the work of the federation and its presidents, reminding that the presidents of the federations do not receive salaries.
Pone also criticized Jakubovski himself, saying that before the London Olympic Games, when Ribakova was not approved among the participants, he appealed to the International Aquatics Federation (FINA) with a complaint and called on Latvia not to send any athletes.
Pone, however, could not say why he is at the Olympic Games with the coach&#39;s accreditation, which probably should have belonged to Jakubovski.
&quot;I was applied as the president of the federation (&quot;team leader&quot;), but for unknown reasons I received the coach&#39;s accreditation and now I can&#39;t get anywhere.&quot;
The situation changed every day, the number of available accreditations changed.
Until the last moment, I thought that German would be there, because I had no other information.
According to the information available to the LETA agency, a couple of days before Ribakova&#39;s start, she had a face-to-face conversation with Poni, after which the swimmer had tears in her eyes, however, the LPF president himself expressed that it was an everyday conversation with the desire to tune the athlete up before the start.
Pone reminded that the LPF oversees five sports that are in the Olympic program, and in four of them training is held for children in Latvia as well.
The president of the Federation expressed that the issues of drowning are also very important in Latvia and he also spoke about such programs when he was in Rio de Janeiro for almost two weeks.
He praised the work of the federation and said that in 2018 the World Cup could be held in Latvia.
Being in Rio de Janeiro is not my vacation, I work here, spend my time and try to implement four-year programs.
600,000 baby salmon will be released into the Daugava.
As part of JSC Latvenergo&#39;s fish resources restoration program, salmon and sea trout juveniles are being released this week in the Daugava near Mangaļsala, and this year it is planned to release more than 600,000 one-year-old salmon and sea trout juveniles raised in the Tomes and Dole fish farms of the scientific institute Bior.
LETA informed the Latvenergo agency that the release of fish will continue in the following months - a total of 6,300,000 fish fry and larvae of various species are released into the water bodies of the Daugava basin every year.
Pike and lamprey larvae will be released in the spring and early summer of 2016, in June - whitefish, in July - one-summer salmon, in August and September - zanders and walleyes.
Latvenergo production director Māris Kunickis said that caring for the environment is one of the cornerstones of the sustainable development of the Latvenergo concern.
&quot;In measures for the protection and propagation of fish resources, everyone&#39;s actions are focused on environmentally friendly actions in close cooperation with the scientific institute Bior, both by raising and releasing fish fry into the Daugava basin, and by implementing other activities&quot;, said Kunickis.
This year, more than 600,000 year-old salmon and trout fry will be released into the Daugava estuary.
For the second year, the baby fish are marked by cutting off the adipose fin before being released.
Today&#39;s shipment includes 25,000 baby salmon with an average weight of 31.3 grams.
Every year, fish fry and larvae are released into the water bodies of the Daugava and its basin in a scientifically based species composition and numerical volume.
The reproduction of fish resources in the Daugava and the water bodies of its basin is carried out by Bior in accordance with the regulatory enactments, based on the expertise of the damage caused to fish resources as a result of Latvenergo&#39;s economic activity and providing a conclusion on what compensation measures should be taken to ensure the diversity of fish resources.
On the other hand, the State Environmental Service, based on the aforementioned expertise, makes a decision on the amount and type of compensation.
Latvenergo&#39;s annual compensation amount in the fish resources restoration program is EUR 1,035,000.
In the spring of 2016, Latvenergo, in cooperation with the association &quot;Mēs zivīm&quot;, placed 400 artificial fish spawning nests in the Daugava near Kaibala and Ikškile for the fifth year.
Cooperation with the association, promoting the natural spawning of fish, is an initiative additionally supported by Latvenergo within the framework of the fish resources restoration program.
Placing artificial spawning nests in the reservoir is an important measure that contributes to the protection and reproduction of fish resources in the Daugava.
The festival &quot;Sanssusi Concert Hall&quot; has a country yard, a forest, a clearing.
Sleep in a tent, eat like in a restaurant, walk in sneakers and listen to sophisticated chamber music, enjoying the quiet peace of nature - this is the combination offered by the alternative chamber music festival in Sanssusi, which is inviting you to Aknīste region for the third summer.
The festival will take place in the yard of the former parish house of Susėja - a village that no longer exists, in the nearby woods and clearings.
In three days - from August 12 to 14 - on five stages you can combine the carefree enjoyment of nature and the refined enjoyment of academic music.
Here, music meets theater and contemporary circus, performances and installations.
Opera and academic music, especially in its latest forms, find new listeners in a free and open environment without the stiffness of concert halls.
The distance from here to Riga is about 150 km, but it only takes a few minutes to get a smile on your face and lightness on your feet.
&quot;Please don&#39;t look for the program, because we have deliberately chosen not to publish it in advance, so that people don&#39;t go to one specific event or artist, because the real taste of Sanssusi can only be captured by spending all three days there,&quot; says the initiator and host of the festival, opera baritone Armands Siliņš.
We open the gates of the festival on Friday at 17.00, and the first concert is at 19.00.
Of course, there will be programs on site with all the information.
For those who have to choose one day, we recommend Saturday, because it is the busiest - from 9.00 in the morning until the next dawn.
&quot;The names of the artists are available on the website www.sansusi.lv&quot;, says Armands Siliņš.
The magnificent bouquet of artists includes, for example, violinist Eva Bindere, cellist Kristīne Blaumane, opera star Inga Kalna, clarinetist Guntis Kuzma, trumpeter Jānis Porietis, pianist Reinis Zariņš, quartets Quadra and RIX and even Estonian aerial acrobat Grete Gross, who together with Latvian musicians Ārik Kiršfeld , Mārtiņa Zilberta and actress Anci Strazda created the contemporary circus show Confines about the artist&#39;s inner struggle.
New works have also been created especially for the festival.
Entomologist (insect researcher) Uģis Piterāns will take part in the children&#39;s show &quot;Kukainis&quot;, composed by Olesja Kozlovska and Jēkabs Nīmanis based on the motifs of F. Kafka&#39;s story Transformation, along with Armandas Siliņas, musicians and actors.
Oskars Herliņš composed the first String Quartet, while Anna ķirse - the Tree Opera, a performance whose main characters will be trees in three small clumps in the three-hectare clearing, directed by Andras Kalnozola, with video projections by Katrīna Neiburgas and scenography by Andras Eglīš.
Singing in the voices of Laima Lediņa, Dināra Rudāne and Zigmāras Graš, they will end up in a romantic relationship, just like in the study of Swedish naturalist Karl Linnaeus of the Enlightenment era, Tree Wedding (1729).
