A French court rejects a claim to demolish shops in the &quot;Jungle&quot; refugee camp.
The French court rejected the request of the Calais authorities to demolish dozens of self-made shops and restaurants in the &quot;Jungle&quot; camp, where several thousand refugees live.
At a court hearing this week in Calais, authorities said the state should demolish 72 self-made shops where people in the camp sell goods such as cigarettes and energy drinks, offer hairdressing services, tea for 50 cents (40p) and simple meals for a few euros. in restaurants.
The Calais prefect&#39;s office said these self-created businesses must be demolished because they create a shadow economy and do not pay taxes, as well as pose fire and sanitary risks.
Representatives of the humanitarian group explained to the court that these small businesses are essential because the food provided by the government and support groups does not meet the needs of the camp, where the number of residents continues to grow.
They also pointed out that self-made shops and restaurants often offer free shelter and food to those who need it most.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to deport the people who set up the 72 self-made shops, but it understood the concerns of the prefect of Calais.
Judge Jean-Francois Moll said food, coffee and restaurateurs play a bigger role than simply providing food to people living in &quot;extremely poor conditions&quot;.
He pointed out that these places are peaceful meeting places for refugees and volunteers.
One site at risk of demolition is the camp&#39;s Jungle Book Kids cafe, which provides more than 200 free meals a day, English and French lessons and asylum counseling to hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect the children&#39;s cafe.
In a letter to the Guardian, the closure of the cafe &quot;would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are as young as 8 years old.&quot;
On Friday, two charitable organizations &quot;Help for Refugees&quot; and &quot;L&#39;Auberge des Migrants&quot; reported that the number of residents of the &quot;Jungle&quot; camp has increased to 9,000 people, which is the highest figure since the rapid influx of migrants in the summer.
