In Spain, the possibility of reducing the budget deficit is threatened by the inability to form a government.
A month ago, on July 12, the European Commission (EC) issued an opinion that Spain and Portugal have not implemented sufficiently extensive measures to reduce the level of the budget deficit to the 3% of the gross domestic product (GDP) required by the Eurozone.
Calculations show that, despite the implemented austerity measures, Portugal&#39;s budget deficit was 4.4% of GDP at the end of last year, while Spain&#39;s was 5.1%.
However, the European Commission decided not to apply economic sanctions to both countries, while at the same time setting fiscal goals for the near future.
One of the reasons why the EC did not introduce sanctions against the two mentioned countries is the growing Euroscepticism in many countries of the European Union.
Additional sanctions would only increase such negative sentiment.
Critics, however, point out that the EC is not consistent in its decisions, agreeing on uniform rules from the beginning and then not being able to apply them in practice.
Thus, for example, the president of the German Bundesbank, Jens Weidmann, has pointed out that Europe is losing confidence in itself in this way, creating the impression in the population that the rules of the European Union are recommendatory, not binding.
Now the EC has proposed and all member states have approved the extension of the budget deficit adjustment deadline until the end of this year for Portugal and until 2018 for Spain.
The European Commission promises to check the progress achieved by both countries in the coming months, at the same time stating that both Spain and Portugal should be ready to implement additional austerity measures if the circumstances require it.
Preliminary forecasts show that Portugal could achieve the set goal on time and already this year the budget deficit could decrease to 2.5% of the gross domestic product.
This means that within the framework of the Stability Program, the government of this country must implement austerity measures of 0.25% of GDP this year.
These measures should be included in this year&#39;s budget, with additional attention paid to controlling the costs of procurement of goods and services.
In the case of Spain, the situation is much more complicated.
This year the budget deficit should be reduced to 4.6%, next year - to 3.1% and in 2018 - to 2.2% of GDP.
In addition, for the next two years, consolidation measures should amount to 0.5% of GDP annually.
Achieving these goals is made especially difficult by the fact that the Spanish political parties have not been able to agree on the formation of a government for eight months, and the possibility that Spain may have to hold early parliamentary elections for the third time in a year is increasing.
However, public opinion polls show that even the third election would not significantly change the political scene in the country.
The most popular party is still the People&#39;s Party led by the current Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, who would again win less than 33% of the vote in the elections.
Only the socialists have slightly increased their popularity, while the popularity of the anti-austerity parties &quot;Podemos&quot; or &quot;Together we can&quot; and &quot;Ciudadanos&quot; or &quot;Citizens&quot; has slightly decreased.
The People&#39;s Party wants to get the socialists and &quot;Ciudadanos&quot; involved in the government this month, otherwise it will not be possible to adopt and submit the 2017 budget draft to the European Commission for approval by mid-October.
As the representative of the parliamentary faction of the People&#39;s Party, Rafael Hernando, has announced, if the government fails to be formed and the parliamentary elections are still held for the third time, Spain will become the laughingstock of the whole of Europe.
The cleanliness of the beaches in the Gulf of Riga is critical.
After surveying the beaches for the fifth year, the activists have concluded that, unfortunately, the number of garbage found increases every year, and visitors to the bathing areas are mostly to blame.
The most polluted swimming spots are exactly in Riga.
The city council explains that the swimming areas are cleaned every day, but it is quite difficult to fight against dirty visitors.
In addition, waste left on land can be washed into the water during rainstorms, thus significantly impairing its quality.
Except for Liepāja beach and certain places in Kurzeme, the cleanliness of beaches in other parts of Latvia is critical.
This announcement was made this week by the volunteers of the &quot;My Sea&quot; campaign.
Measuring the road along the Gulf of Riga on foot for the fifth year, activists have concluded that the amount of waste left by residents has increased every hundred meters.
Unfortunately, this year, that assessment of criticality has come.
&quot;We see that this will be a year when the amount of garbage on 100 meters of the beach may even exceed 200 items,&quot; says Jānis Ulme, representative of the &quot;Mana jūra&quot; expedition.
Called by Latvian Radio, he was on the beach of Tūja, where the march of volunteers continues along the Gulf of Riga.
This year, among various household waste and remains of picnics, activists even had to collect fluorescent lamps, which were left lying in the sea sand.
Ulme, a participant and organizer of the hike, says that the residents are to blame for the pollution.
&quot;The main source is the beach visitors themselves, because more than half of the total amount of waste is plastic, various waste, starting with bags, pieces of plastic that are already in the stage of degradation, it is no longer possible to identify them, and cigarette butts, bottles, corks,&quot; says Ulm.
Swimming places in Riga are also among the dirtiest beaches.
For example, in Daugavgrīva, almost 800 waste units are collected every hundred meters, which is a critical amount.
The organizers of the campaign also explain that cigarette butts are thrown at almost every step and warning or prohibition signs are not everywhere.
&quot;The average figures for all three Riga swimming areas together - Daugavgrīva, Vakarbulli and Vecākai - are unfortunately high and far exceed the desired or goal that Latvia is supposedly moving towards, to reduce the number of waste units to 135 units by 2020&quot;, concludes the environmentalist.
Cleaning of swimming areas in Riga takes place every day, even twice on the hottest days of summer, explains Uģis Vidauskis, the representative of the city council.
However, the fight against dirty visitors is quite difficult.
We return to the question of the culture of these people.
&quot;Even special signs do not affect those who fertilize, drink alcohol, smoke and do all those things that are not allowed&quot;, says Vidauskis.
That&#39;s why Vidauskis calls on visitors to swimming areas to report pollutants to the police as well.
You can call the police, safely point out these violations and fight everyone in this way.
Maybe some new warnings can be imposed, but as I said, it is unlikely to radically change the situation.
&quot;Because everyone should simply address and be intolerant of such violators together,&quot; he emphasizes.
Meanwhile, water quality measurements have been carried out for the fourth time this summer by the Health Inspectorate, which can impose a ban on official swimming places.
This year, as in other years, the water quality is said to be good and satisfactory everywhere.
The current situation is that in all 56 swimming areas the water quality has been good all the time and there are no bathing restrictions.
&quot;We will take the analyzes for the last time at the end of August&quot;, says Normunds Kadiķis, the inspector&#39;s senior specialist in environmental health issues.
Garbage left on land can be washed into the water during heavy rains.
This, in turn, can affect its quality, says an environmentalist.
