A dying man was robbed on the side of the road in the capital of India.
In the capital of India, no one seems to know about a man who was knocked down and dying on the side of the road - it turns out that he was lying on the side of the road for an hour and then he was robbed, the BBC informs.
The man, identified as Matibool, reportedly drove a rickshaw during the day and worked as a security guard at night.
Matibul was walking home on the road at 5:30 in the morning when he was hit by a car.
The recording of the surveillance cameras shows that the driver got out of the car to look at the victim and then drove away.
An hour later, when no one seemed to know about the bleeding man, he was robbed by a thug.
About 90 minutes after the crash, the police arrived at the scene and the victim was taken to the hospital, where he died from his injuries.
By withdrawing her candidacy for the post of Director General of the State Revenue Service (SRS), the head of the State Environmental Service, Inga Koļegova, has saved the government from falling, believes Ojārs Skudra, associate professor of the Faculty of Social Sciences of the University of Latvia.
Kolegova&#39;s explanation for withdrawing her candidacy due to contradictions in the ruling coalition is related to the fact that she prevented the fall of the government.
In a conversation with LETA agency, Sudra said that it is difficult for him to imagine that &quot;Vienotība&quot; would support Kolegova&#39;s candidacy at the next week&#39;s government meeting.
Therefore, if the ministers of &quot;Unity&quot; voted against, but still confirmed Kolegova, it would lead to the resignation of the government.
Also, the expert believes that before announcing the withdrawal of her candidacy, Kolegova consulted both Finance Minister Dana Reiznieci-Ozola and Prime Minister Mari Kučinski.
At the same time, it is said to be a concession to &quot;Unity&quot;, which strongly opposed her candidacy.
Predicting whether it will be possible to find a suitable candidate through the competition, Skudra admitted that there are two options - either a compromise figure will be selected, or Dace Pelekas will continue to lead the institution as acting general director.
At the same time, he points out - if the Minister of Finance has claimed until now that no other candidacy is being considered, this is a hint to Pelekaya that she should not participate in the competition.
