In a statement issued Thursday, the House of Congress says that representatives of the US Central Command have distorted reports, portraying the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria as more optimistic than it actually is.
Central Command intelligence analysts expressed widespread dismay at the interim report from a task force created by Republican representatives of the Armed Services Committee, the Intelligence Committee and the Defense Appropriations Subcommittee, saying their leadership controlled reports on American progress in the fight against the Islamic State.
Central Command, known as Centcom, is a military base in Tampa, Florida that oversees US military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
The latest news on the report is that intelligence reports approved by high-ranking Centcom executives paint a more positive picture of the US fight against terrorism than it actually is. The facts were routinely distorted to portray a better performance than other intelligence analyses.
Rep. Ken Calvert, Republican of California, said: &quot;Centcom&#39;s actions are unacceptable - our soldiers are the ones who suffer when our policymakers receive false information.&quot;
Centcom&#39;s management mistakes can be traced back to the top management of the organization.
This 10-page report details problems in Central Command&#39;s coverage and analysis of American efforts to prepare Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While this does not provide conclusive evidence that senior Obama administration officials ordered the reports to be distorted, it does suggest that Centcom management exerted some pressure on analysts to portray a more optimistic view of the threat posed by the Islamic State (also known as ISIS or ISIL).
The report notes that in the first half of 2015, the Central Administration&#39;s press releases, announcements and reports to Congress portrayed the situation in a significantly more positive light than it actually was.
For example, Centcom representatives publicly announced that the operation to retake Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul is Iraq&#39;s second largest city still under the control of the Islamic State.
Mike Pompeo, a spokesman for the Kansas Republican Party, said in a report: &quot;A months-long investigation makes this clear.&quot;
Between mid-2014 and mid-2015, key US Central Command officials distorted reports to portray the ISIS threat in Iraq as weaker than it actually was.
The Republican Party created the task force after learning that analysts were concerned that information about the Islamic State was being distorted.
Thursday&#39;s report will follow new findings in the case as the investigation continues.
The General Inspectorate of the Ministry of Defense is conducting an investigation into the activities of the Centcom intelligence service.
The Democratic members of the Intelligence Management Committee released their own report Thursday, in which they agree with some of the findings of the Republican task force.
Representative Adam B. Schiff, a Democrat, said in his report that from 2014 to 2015, Centcom excessively restricted the preparation of intelligence assessment reports related to ISIS and the Iraqi Security Forces.
Mr. Schiff explains that the process &quot;stopped the flow of information,&quot; undermined analysts&#39; work ethics, and &quot;proliferated false facts.&quot;
But Schiff and fellow Democrats added that there was no evidence that the White House had pressured Centcom analysts to produce reports in line with a &quot;predetermined or political position.&quot;
The Daily Beast published the preliminary results of the congressional investigation on Thursday.
In August, The New York Times reported that the Pentagon&#39;s inspector general had opened an investigation following complaints from Centcom analysts.
Pentagon spokesman Lt. Commander Patrick Evans said the Pentagon would not comment on the congressional report pending an investigation.
He also added that experts sometimes interpret complex data in different ways, and the Ministry of Defense and the Intelligence Agency call for a constructive dialogue on vital national security issues.
The inquiry is not limited to whether the American-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is succeeding (a claim made by a growing number of Defense Department officials).
But last year&#39;s allegations call into question whether President Obama can fully rely on reports from the Central Command about military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan and other hot spots.
Criticism of Islamic State intelligence echoes more than a decade ago, when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker released a study alleging that the George W. Bush administration launched the war in Afghanistan with too little thought for its potential consequences.
Hooker also played a major role in uncovering the Islamic State intelligence issue.
Last year, officials reported that Hooker&#39;s team had found that, contrary to public reports, airstrikes on Islamic State oil facilities had not significantly dented the terrorist group&#39;s financial position because they had built makeshift factories to sell oil on the black market.
The Times reported in its September edition that this discovery did not go beyond the walls of the Central Administration.
The commander of Centcom at the time, General Lloyd Austin III, received sharp criticism because many law makers believed that the war reports described the situation too positively.
In April, General Austin retired and was replaced by General Joseph L. Votel.
