The most depressing food of the depression period is the &quot;Heavy Meal&quot;
In March 1933, shortly after being elected president, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down to a meal in the Oval Office.
President Roosevelt enjoyed fine culinary delicacies such as foie gras and Maryland turtle soup.
However, that day his meal was much more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and plum pudding for dessert.
Jane Ziegelman says, &quot;It&#39;s a way of showing solidarity in cooking with people who have had a really hard time.&quot;
Adds her husband, Andrew Coe, &quot;It&#39;s also a message to Americans about how to eat.&quot;
A couple from Brooklyn Heights are food historians.
Kou&#39;s latest book &quot;Vegetable Stew&quot; describes Chinese cuisine in America, while Ziegelmane in her book &quot;97 Apples&quot; describes life through food in a tenement house on the Lower East Side of Manhattan.
Their new joint effort, &quot;The Hearty Meal,&quot; to be published Tuesday by Harper&#39;s, is the story of American food during the Great Depression.
Showing some culinary solidarity, they dined together with the reporter at Eisenberg&#39;s Sandwich Shop, a casual diner in the Flatirons that has been open since 1929, when the Great Depression began.
Mrs. Ziegelmanes, 54, ordered a sandwich with melted cheese and chopped olives, while Kou, 57, ordered turkey, mashed potatoes and vegetable salad.
When the reporter ordered the fake bunny, the couple admitted that his choice was very appropriate for a conversation about Great Depression-era food.
Ms. Ziegelman said the fake bunny was very popular.
There was a peanut bunny, a liver bunny, and a bean bunny.
They were made from a basic ingredient and other ingredients that enriched the meal.
Imagine what it&#39;s like to eat enough peanuts for lunch.
Mr. Kou was startled.
&quot;It must have felt like a stomach full of lead,&quot; he added.
In the pre-Depression years, the American dinner table resembled a Swedish table, especially in rural areas.
Women cooked for their laborer husbands and freshly prepared concoctions were served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
During the First World War, it was the Americans who sent food to the Europeans. &quot;The Hearty Meal&quot; describes how Americans adapted to the conditions when America was suddenly no longer a land of plenty.
&quot;At that time, food became the main focus of the American people on a daily basis,&quot; says Mr. Kou, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write about this particular topic.
Equally important were the new budget diets: unknown dishes like fake hare and stews became commonplace, stews were &quot;a great way to use up leftovers,&quot; noted Ms. Ziegelman, because cooks could hide unappealing ingredients under a creamy sauce.
Fresh fruit was replaced by cheap dried fruit.
Meat, which had been a staple of American meals for years, now became an extremely rare luxury item.
At a time when the number of calories and the nutritional value of food were more important than taste, new, never-before-seen creations were born.
In an old cookbook, Ms. Ziegelman found a recipe for peanut butter-stuffed onions.
Mr Kou adds: &quot;It was not a popular addition to the dinner table.&quot;
Ms. Ziegelman emphasizes: &quot;It was surreal.&quot;
Peanut butter and fried onion do not go together.
Many home cooking recipes adapted to the hard times.
Household economists such as Louise Stanley, head of the Federal Bureau of Household Economics from 1923 to 1943, defined national eating patterns not seen before or since the Great Depression.
By publishing articles and recipes in newspapers and magazines, they advised housewives to become &quot;economists&quot; and take on challenges such as turning a pasta and carrot mixture into a tasty meal.
&quot;Heavy Meal&quot; is a feast of historical delicacies.
Of particular interest are the testimonies of the government&#39;s attitude towards its hungry citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover&#39;s &quot;let me eat cake&quot; attitude.
Although in public he talked about his simple childhood and dining in Iowa, in reality he ate like the fine millionaire he had become.
Mr. Kou says: &quot;He liked European cuisine, like fish with cucumber sauce.&quot;
He ate in an almost gilded drawing room, wearing a dinner jacket.
He was completely detached from reality.
President Roosevelt would have made the same mistake if his wife Eleanor hadn&#39;t advised him to set an example with his eating habits.
The book says that Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who couldn&#39;t cook, so the White House became a place &quot;where not only was one of the most unappetizing meals served in Washington, but also the worst prepared meals.&quot;
As the nation&#39;s economy recovered, most Depression-era culinary customs disappeared.
But we continue to focus on calories and nutrition, and how to apply science to cooking, Ms. Ziegelman added.
The couple say that writing the book gave them a better understanding of Ms. Ziegelman&#39;s mother&#39;s eating habits, such as why she couldn&#39;t throw away food.
&quot;She was really afraid to throw the food out,&quot; Mr Kou said.
Ms. Ziegelman said, &quot;She was actually driving people crazy.&quot;
Once there was an incident with wind cakes.
After we ate at Eisenberg&#39;s, a couple of writers pulled a homemade dessert out of their bag: the plum pudding that President Roosevelt used to eat for lunch.
&quot;It&#39;s plum whipped cream,&quot; Ms. Ziegelman said, adding that it was common at the time to give modest dishes a fancy name.
It has no whipped cream, just prunes, a little flour, sugar, water and cinnamon.
Everyone eagerly dipped their spoons into the brown mass on their plates.
Surprisingly, it wasn&#39;t that bad.
Mr. Kou ate a few more bites.
Sounding like an experienced &quot;economist,&quot; he told his wife, &quot;A pinch of ground hazelnuts would do.&quot;
