Britain must maintain the Olympic spirit and expand Heathrow.
Heathrow will not only contribute to prosperity and growth in local areas and London, but across the country as well.
This, I think, makes Heathrow very attractive, just like in London in 2012, where we put in a huge amount of work to ensure that all regions of the country benefit from the Olympic Games.
Stratford and the East End gained enormously from the Olympics.
And we will do it again, providing local people and businesses with business opportunities close to Heathrow.
For local communities alone, we will create 10,000 new business opportunities, 40,000 new jobs and finally put an end to youth unemployment in the Heathrow area.
As with the London Olympics in 2012, there will be people who think the challenge is too great and that the expansion of Heathrow is too ambitious.
At the time, people said that Britain would never be able to prepare for the Olympics in time and that it would be a global failure.
The skeptics were wrong about 2012 and they will not be right in the case of Heathrow either.
There are always obstacles to overcome, but Heathrow has overcome them so far.
Like the Olympics, Heathrow is an infrastructure project that will benefit society as a whole, not individuals.
The expansion has the potential to create up to 180,000 new jobs, an economic boost of £211 billion, creating the ground for both employment and experience at this airport and across the UK.
Heathrow has a great team that has delivered an £11 billion infrastructure investment program on time and on budget, from Terminal 5, which has been named the best airport terminal in the world five years in a row, to Terminal 2, built between the two most intensively used runways in the world.
Now they are ready to build a third runway, which will be financed by private investment of 16 billion pounds.
The London 2012 Olympics were a great success and I&#39;m sure the Heathrow expansion will be as well.
It is time to revive the Olympic spirit and expand Heathrow, securing the future of our trade and creating a new employment environment that Britain can be proud of.
Lord Paul Deighton is a board member of Heathrow and former business secretary at the Ministry of the Economy.
In Switzerland, a woman runs onto the highway in an attempt to commit suicide.
The victim lay down on the highway in the middle of the night.
Police are trying to find witnesses to the accident when she was run over by several cars on the highway early Thursday morning.
The accident happened shortly after midnight on Thursday on the A1 road near the town of Morges in the canton of Vaud.
A police report from the Canton of Vaux said that in a desperate attempt to commit suicide, the woman had laid down on the road in the dark where she was run over by several cars.
While clearly trying to kill himself, the victim, a 49-year-old Swiss man, was hit by several cars, including a lorry.
She died at the scene.
Several drivers involved in the accident have already given statements, but others involved have yet to be identified, say the police, who are appealing to the drivers involved and witnesses to the accident to come forward.
A criminal investigation has also been launched into the case, which is a logical step in such a case, lawyer Gilles Hofsteller told Le Tribune de Geneve.
However, it is not yet known whether any of the drivers involved will be punished.
Was the collision avoidable?
Hofsteller adds: &quot;That will be determined by the prosecutor.&quot;
Two similar cases that have occurred in the last 5 years show that none of the drivers will be prosecuted.
In both cases, the pedestrian had walked onto the highway in the middle of the night, so it was decided that the drivers could not foresee that a pedestrian would be on the highway in the middle of the night, the newspaper reports.
Last year, a policewoman was acquitted of manslaughter when she ran over a man who was sleeping on the A1 near Payjerne in the middle of the night in August 2014.
The court found out that the 22-year-old victim had been drinking and later fell asleep on the road.
The court concluded that the policewoman who was on her way to the scene of the accident was driving in a manner appropriate to the circumstances, and the judge recognized that the sleeping man on the road was a &quot;completely unpredictable and extraordinary case&quot;.
Anyone with information about Thursday&#39;s accident near Morges is urged to contact police on 021 644 83 46 or 021 644 44 44.
