Due to a neighbor&#39;s repairs, the man is faced with a collapsed ceiling and is forced to leave the house.
In LTV&#39;s &quot;4.studija&quot; program, Dmitrij Saidyashevs appealed, whose neighbor started major repairs in his apartment, and since then, Dmitrij&#39;s plaster is crumbling from the ceiling and he is not sure that it is safe to stay in the apartment.
The problem is that my neighbors did arbitrary construction and the ceiling in my apartment is damaged.
Then I informed the Riga construction board, the building manager and other organizations.
The building authority said that we are not an operative service and we do not have any expert.
&quot;The owner of the apartment has to go to the Union of Engineers of Latvia, and there will be an expert from there,&quot; says Dmitrijs.
The invited expert arrived, recorded the incident and admitted that the cover was in an unsatisfactory condition.
However, a month has passed since Dmitri&#39;s first application to the building board, and until the beginning of this week, no one was able to answer whether being in the apartment is not life-threatening.
The building authority said - such is the legislation, wait, if you are not satisfied, write to everyone in turn.
&quot;Then I wrote to the Riga City Council, but they forwarded it to the building manager, then the building manager again to the building board, and then there is a dead end&quot;, says Dmitrijs.
After looking through the whole pile of papers, it is clear that the construction works have been stopped, even if you can hear that someone is working there every now and then.
Expertise should be carried out within another two months, and within six months the owner of the apartment, who is carrying out repairs, should eliminate all these defects.
The independent expert has developed his opinion, but the construction board considers it incomplete and superficial.
The expert has not indicated whether the metal grating in this load-bearing structure has been affected, so there is no certainty that the owner of the lower apartment is at risk.
&quot;That&#39;s why we have requested an additional explanation from this expert&quot;, says Ilze Žūka, representative of the Riga City Construction Board.
Despite the ban on carrying out any repairs in the upper apartment, from there you can still hear that the construction is going on.
The penalty for arbitrary construction without a building permit is from 70 to 700 euros, but in the specific case the penalty can be much more severe.
While the expert&#39;s opinion is awaited, the construction board has decided that both apartments may not be operated - both the one where construction works are underway and Dmitri&#39;s apartment.
&quot;This is an unprecedented case in the construction board&#39;s practice, when in this way, due to their ignorance or simply unwillingness, residents may have created a danger not only to their own property, but also to the owner of the lower property, as a result of which this owner cannot operate his property&quot;, says the representative of the building board.
Now Dmitri has to look for another place to live - with relatives, friends, in a hotel or to rent another apartment.
But Dmitriy can try to collect the resulting losses from the neighbor in civil law, which can take a lot of time.
Due to the arbitrary construction, staying in both apartments is currently prohibited until the construction engineer gives his conclusion, which may take up to three weeks.
The owner of the apartment in which the repairs took place will have to cover the resulting damages.
The owner of this apartment, due to the fact that he did not take into account what the construction board said, also faces a prison sentence of up to six months.
