NASA climate model: Venus was once a habitable planet
Based on NASA&#39;s latest climate models, Venus was once a habitable planet.
Scientists at NASA&#39;s Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to study the history of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, which has a hot surface with no water and an atmosphere composed almost entirely of carbon, ever had Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously speculated that Venus&#39;s slow rotation rate can be explained by its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulations show that Venus once had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and that it rotated slowly.
The model also looks at the past topography of Venus.
The planet had more dry areas than Earth, but had enough water and geographic diversity to support life and prevent water from evaporating.
In the early days of Venus, the Sun was 30 percent brighter.
A GISS model simulation of Venus&#39; rotation model reveals that the bright part of the day on it lasts for 2 months, GISS scientist Antony Del Genio explained in a press release.
This process heats the planet&#39;s surface and causes rain, which in turn forms layers of thick clouds that act as an umbrella, shielding the planet from the Sun&#39;s heat.
The result is a temperate climate that is actually a few degrees cooler than the temperature on Earth today.
The model represents the history of Venus, similar to the theory of evolution that scientists have developed in their hypotheses.
Although once habitable, Venus has been exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet radiation over the course of several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated, and its vapors were burned by ultraviolet rays.
When the water completely evaporated, all that was left was a thin atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse gas - Venus as we know it today.
The scientists published the results of the new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
Patrick Roy resigns as Avalanche coach
On Thursday, Colorado Avalanche coach and vice president of hockey operations Patrick Roy resigned, citing insufficient influence in the team&#39;s decision-making process.
Colorado vice president and general manager Joe Sakic confirmed the news and said the club will begin searching for a new coach immediately.
&quot;For the past three years, I have filled my duties as head coach and vice president of hockey operations for Colorado Club with energy, passion and purpose,&quot; Roy, 50, said in a statement.
During this summer, I have been thinking a lot about how I can improve the performance of the team to give it the shine it needs and achieve a higher level of results.
To achieve this, the visions of the head coach and vice president of hockey operations must fully align with the visions of the organization.
He should also be able to influence decisions related to team performance.
Currently, these conditions are not met.
Sakik, who hired Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked Roy for his contributions to the team.
Sakik said Patrick informed him of his decision today.
We appreciate everything he has done for the organization and wish him all the best in the future.
In his first season with the &quot;Avalanche&quot; team in 2013-2014. Roy was recognized as the best coach in the league and received the Jack Adams award.
He helped the club reach 112 points and first place in the Central Division, but in the first round of the playoffs, the Colorado team was defeated by the Minnesota hockey players. Since then, the club has not made the playoffs for two years.
&quot;Avalanche&quot; concluded the 2015-2016 season. 2018 season with a score of 39-39-4 and remained five points behind the &quot;Wild&quot; team, failing to receive the second special invitation from the organizers of the Western Conference.
A Hall of Fame goaltender, Roy won four Stanley Cups in his career - two with the Montreal Canadiens and two with the Avalanche.
North Sea oil rig workers resume talks and postpone strike
Workers&#39; strikes over the wages of workers on North Sea oil platforms have been postponed, as both sides involved in the dispute have resumed negotiations, according to negotiators.
Strikes are periodically held against the oil processing company &quot;Wood Group&quot; on the North Sea oil platforms where the company &quot;Royal Dutch Shell&quot; operates.
The joint statement states that the Wood Group and Unite and RMT unions have agreed to resume negotiations to resolve the dispute.
A number of full-day meetings are scheduled over the coming weeks, starting early next week, with the aim of revisiting the problematic issues.
The unions said their latest action, organized after a hiatus of more than 25 years, was against a planned 30 percent wage cut.
Due to negative market pressure, &quot;Wood Group&quot; reduced the salaries of employees in the North Sea by 9 percent this year.
Already in 2014, the company reduced the wages of land workers by 10 percent.
The company explains that the additional salary cuts would allow the company to survive the market downturn.
Shell, on the other hand, has already cut the wages of several thousand people and announced plans to shut down oil and natural gas operations in 10 countries to optimize its work as it prepares for a large-scale merger deal with British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure due to falling oil prices, and the situation is further complicated by Britain&#39;s decision to leave the European Union.
Earlier in the week, Scottish MP Dave Anderson met with workers&#39; representatives to discuss one of the most important issues - North Sea strike plans.
He said the North Sea was vital to the region&#39;s economy.
In his report, he explains that the North Sea and the country as a whole need an economy that benefits everyone, not just individuals.
Almost $1.4 billion is expected to be invested in new North Sea projects in 2016, compared to $7 billion invested over the past five years.
Kepler measured the rotation speed of the stars in the Pleiades constellation.
The latest mission of the Kepler telescope has helped astronomers compile the most complete catalog of the rotation rates of stars in the Pleiades constellation.
The new data helps astronomers understand why the stars in this constellation rotate at different speeds, as well as how the rotation speed of the stars is attributed to the formation of planets.
&quot;We hope that by comparing our results with other constellations, we will gain more information about the relationship between the star&#39;s mass, age, and even the history of its solar system,&quot; Luisa Rebula, a scientist at Caltech&#39;s Infrared Process and Analytical Center in Pasadena, said in a news release.
The Pleiades constellation is located 445 light years from Earth.
Many stars in this constellation are just beginning to grow, reaching an age of about 125 million years.
They spin at maximum speed.
As they rotate at maximum speed, these accreting stars emit large amounts of stellar wind.
As the winds enter the star&#39;s magnetic field, they slow down the stars.
As stars age, their rotation speed decreases.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star, determining the time between the appearance of recognizable regions of stars, such as sunspots.
The latest catalog of stellar rotation rates shows that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, taller dancers do pirouettes slower than shorter dancers.
Rebul says that the &quot;ballet&quot; of the Pleiades shows that the slowly rotating objects are larger and more massive, while the faster rotating objects are very small stars.
Because the Pleiades constellation is so close, it serves as an excellent space laboratory where the characteristics of stars can be compared with their rotation rates.
Rebull says that the Pleiades constellation is helping to build theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions for both older and younger stars.
We still have a lot to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down, and about the process of their coming to a complete stop.
Reboul and his colleagues detailed their analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades stars in three new papers to be published soon in the Astronomical Journal.
